Bring a #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the @egg noodle nests{2}.

When boiling, add the noodles and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{}. 

> TIP: Run the noodles under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on medium-high heat.

When hot, add the @chicken thigh{260%g}(diced) and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry, stirring
occasionally, until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Meanwhile, halve the @plums{2}, remove the stones and chop each half into three wedges.

Trim the @pak choi{1} then thinly slice widthways.

Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Lower the heat to medium and add the plums and @sugar{1} to the pan with the chicken.

Stir-fry until the plums start to colour, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @ginger puree{1/2%tsp} along with half the spring onion and as many
@chilli flakes{1%tsp} as you like.

> Careful - chilli flakes are hot.

Stir-fry for another ~{1%minute}.

Add the bok choy and stir-fry until just soft, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @hoisin sauce{32%g}, @ketjap manis{25%g} and @water{25%ml} for the sauce, ensuring
everything is well coated.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan. Stir together and cook until everything is piping hot,
~{1-2%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Divide the chicken and plum stir-fry between your #bowls{}.

Scatter over the @salted peanuts{25%g} and remaining spring onion to serve. Enjoy!